I won’t go into the bearing replacement because it requires a lot more info and the press tool is essential. So, to replace your tub seal only, you will need: a putty knife, a 7/16” socket, a philips screw driver or drill with the philips bit, a wood screw, possibly a car jack and a piece of 2by4 wood cut to approx 21” long. All purpose adhesive which you can buy at most big stores, it’s about $2, I also use some shellack but it’s not essential. So the method: look at the back of your washer, if it has two 1/4” bolts on a green hinge just remove the top screw. Then on the front of the washer where the top meets the base, use your putty knife in the crack, around 6” in from each end there is a catch that you have to push back to release the top of the washer, try lifting the top as you push the putty knife back. Now the top is up, use a pair of pliers that I don’t mention earlier to release the spring catch on the hose at the back of the drum. Then go around the drum cover and release the clips, remove the cover and hose. Use a flat head screw driver and remove the center cap on the wash pulsator. Use the 7/16” socket to remove the bolt, lift the pulsator out, if it’s jammed in there try pushing a screwdriver into the holes close to the bolt and lift. Remove the 6 philips screws holding the tub hub on, be careful because they are soft and you can ruin the screw easily, if you do you will have to drill the screw out. Lift out the two parts of the tub hub. Try lifting the tub out with a helper, if it won’t come out you will need to use the car jack and wood, search YouTube for the method, it’s easier than trying to explain. Once the tub is out you will see the old seal at the base of the shaft. Take the wood screw and screw it in to the edge of the old seal and pull it out with pliers, if it won’t budge try using an extra screw on the other side. Once it’s out, clean up the rim and inspect the bearing. Make sure you grease the inside of the new seal, liberally rub it into the grooves on the INSIDE of the seal. Then holding the seal put a very liberal amount of your adhesive all around the outer rim the the seal, use plenty! Then you can very carefully place the tub seal over the shaft and gently push it down until it has seated. I use a plastic tube and a mallet to seat it fully but you could tap it down gently in a circular motion until it’s pushed right down, then get more adhesive and put it around the top edge where the seal meets the tub. Backtracking a few steps, when you remove the old seal, there is a small weep hole in the 4 o clock position, stick something down the to make sure it’s clean, a straightened paper clip or small screwdriver. Now reassemble the washer and leave the adhesive to cure for 24hrs. The seal will not repair seized bearings, an old seal causes seized bearings so if your washer makes a sound like a bag of rocks or a jet taking off you should replace the bearings too. This job would take me around 30 mins to complete so give yourself 90 mins because I have done hundreds of them.
I know it’s long winded but it’s better for you if you know what’s involved before you decide to try this job. The pitfalls are that the pulsator can be jammed on the shaft. I have had to use a grinder and cut off the whole thing and put a new one in, or the tub won’t come out, hence the car jack. I would recommend replacing the bearings too because you are in there, that would involve a hex wrench and a few other tools but once done you will be proud of yourself for saving over $300 in labor. Given a user purchased an an item with the following details, predict the next 10 items the user would purchase. Item id is <|item_B07X3C8GMC|>. Rating of the item by user from 1 to 5 is 5.0. Text of the user review is There are several places your washer can leak from:

1) One is the seal around the “breathing” snorkel/inlet-outlet which allows for the air inside of the tub to self adjust its inside pressure (due to adding /removing water and heat expansion etc.) automatically. This on our Old Maytag is in the middle of the left inner panel towards the back - centered about 5 inches off the tub floor. It’s a funny leak as depending on how you load the washer - like with a cutting board or plate up against this inlet/outlet - it may or may not leak - but when it does - it leaks pretty well. The seal to fix this problem is often hard to find and more easily replaced buy carefully removing the inside and outside pieces - cleaning them and the side panel they penetrate and putting them all back together with silicone.

Another place where a leak can happen is in from around the door panel seal - Case in point our 23+ YO Maytag PDB3430AWX was leaking around the seal - small stead leak when running - dripping from the left bottom of the door panel. Usually this can be fixed by either adjusting the door latch position - which fastens and tightens with a single bolt (see images) - This is a simple fix - where it is best to mark the current position of the latch with a pencil mark on top before loosening the bolt from below (just inside the tub’s top lip) - then loosening the bolt - SLIGHTLY - moving the latch inward (say1/16-1/8 in) - re-tightening the holding bolt - and testing for moderate - but still easy close and open.

THIS DOOR LATCH ADJUSTMENT IS ALSO NECESSARY WHEN REPLACING THE DOOR SEAL

Adjusting the old seal - If you are getting a door seal leak (as above) and think you want to replace 1st try gently “cleaning and fluffing” the old seal out a bit. This needs to be done gently as your seal may be very weak and may tear - which will be even worse. In general what you’re up to is loosening the seal - which can be “glued” by a combination of old detergent and calcium build up - after loosening the seal along the sides and cleaning off the buildup - CAREFULLY - bring out the seal and gently re-seat without pushing back into the seal groove too far. Test this doing a quick rinse and drain - if good - you’re done - if still leaking - recheck to see how the seal is seated - especially on the leaking side - then try SLIGHTLY adjusting the door seal - (as above) for a tighter seal.

Finally you’ve got the same leak along the door panel and have decided to replace the gasket itself - For us the original door gasket worked well for our 20 something year old Maytag then at one point it didn’t - which is why we 1st did the above cleaning and reseating and latch adjustment approach - which worked well for another year - until we finally decided to get a replacement seal. Just to let you know a Maytag OEM seal replacement for our old dishwasher runs between $60 to $85 delivered - which is why working with this (darn close replicant) seal is worth your while.

Again remove the excess gunk from the gasket and gently remove the original gasket starting from the bottom on one side - not pulling on the gasket - but rather helping it gently release (as needed) from the tub.

Thoroughly clean out the seal’s groove - and begin to place the new seal (as in the one purchased above) into the tub’s seal-groove starting on one side. As you insert and gently press the seal into place - DO NOT STRECH the seal - come all the way around the tub to the opposite end and be sure to cut a little long - then take small cuts to get to the perfect length.

Press the new gasket evenly well into the groove - as it will for sure - by its new nature - fill more of the space than the old seal - with the inside edge of the new seal definitely be inside of the tub’s inside-edge - and pushed in evenly side to side. Finally with a smooth 4-5 inch long x ~ 1/4-5/16 (SMOOTH - NON SHARP) wide piece of wood or tool - tamp the seal all the way around to seat it. The seal should be evenly set all the way around the tub.

Now that you’ve replaced the old seal with something that will fill the grove better - you will probably find that the door will NOT CLOSE! - WOW you may be on your way to fixing this - you just need to do the above door latch adjustment to make a gently firm latching and opening possible - one bolt and a little testing should do the trick.

Finally - test your new seal with a rinse and drain cycle. If things still leak - check where it comes from - if still the door - recheck your seal work and latch setting - if other - then the new seal may be perfect and there may be another place the leak is occurring.

Best of luck!. Main category of the item is Appliances. Text of the user review is Brand new LG model LRMVC2306S refrigerator that takes filter number ADQ747935 (LT-1000P). I'll admit I was very hesitant to purchase any aftermarket filter for LG after reading numerous reviews about the plastic mount in the refrigerator getting damaged. I've included three photos. Notice that the photo of the mounting of these Waterdrop filters I received at the end of Feb 2023 do not look the same as the ones in the bad reviews. However, also notice how different the mounting looks from my original LG filter. I have included a photo of the refrigerator mounting fixture so you can see that the new design IS compatible with the refrigerator after all. It's properly keyed where the mounting half-moon shaped pins fit perfectly into the holes and mates without issue. The plastic tab across the middle also fits perfectly into a slot on the mount. All that matters is that the two half-moon shaped keys fit down into the filter neck WHEN the outer neck tabs are aligned. I did NOT need to make any modifications or use any tools to rotate the inner mount. Everything lined up perfectly and worked properly on the first try.

Align the tabs, push in while rotating CW, and then you should hear a brief little whoosh. It's not the sound of breaking plastic... it's the sound of the valve releasing and letting water pressure into the new filter. Immediately dispense water and you should get a lot of air purging out if everything is connected and working. I only had air for 5 or 10 seconds, but purged and dumped more than a gallon of water.

My original LG filter lasted only 90 days even though it's rated for 200 gallons. That's pretty terrible considering LG wants more than $50 for it. But It's not a surprise since this filter is very small compared to other similar brands like Samsung. The filter in my Samsung, which was 2x larger, always lasted 6 months, both the Samsung and the Waterdrop brand. After 90 days, my LG water started smelling like rotten eggs. I suppose this has to do with overall incoming water quality. I popped in this Waterdrop filter; the smell is gone and the taste is good. At this price I do not mind changing them every 90 days, and some day I may install an RO system and remove the need for a filter in the LG altogether.

Since it's only been 90 days, I did not change the air filter. However, the included air filters appear to be as good as OEM. It's hard to judge this as I do not normally have refrigerators odors.

Filter Change Indicator Light: People really seem to be confused by this. They believe that the refrigerator knows when a filter is bad and/or knows when it's been changed. It does not. The indicator light is merely a 6-month timer. After 6-months, the light comes on even if your filter is still good. In my case, my filter went bad after only 3 months so I never got an indicator light. When the light comes on, and after you change the filter, you must MANUALLY reset the light. Follow the instructions to reset and the light will stay off for the next 6 months. For me, I followed the reset procedure anyway. Either it worked and I won't see the light for 6 more months, or it did nothing and I still have 3 months left on the original timer. Since I have a separate Air filter indicator light that I dod not touch, I will either get both lights on the same day or I won't. I will EDIT this review as I learn more.. Text of the user review is While the overall concept of this is good, the PVC ends of this are just way too big and bulky to really take advantage of the point this is trying to accomplish. I ended up having to remove one of the ends because it was too bulky to fit into the recessed dryer vent housing in my wall. Fighting to get the flex duct on the recessed duct was a chore, but luckily I made it work. While the elbow that connects to the back of the dryer is nice, it too takes up a lot of space and holds the dryer about 6" away from the wall, which isn't ideal in an already tight laundry room.

Overall, I was able to make it work to meet my needs and the duct is definitely more sturdy than most of the cheap-o models in the stores, but unless you have tons of space for clearance at every connection point, you're probably going to find that this isn't as good as it looks..... A screw in the interior assembly extends into the filter area. It catches on the felt gasket and tears it loose from the frame. This gap allows excess lint to get past the filter. This can lead to lint build up in the ducting (fire danger).
THE FIX: use high temp epoxy to reinforce the bottom third of the frame to filter connection. (Remember kids, this is a higher temperature location!) The epoxy is used like caulk between the felt and the plastic. Don't get it on the felt away from the frame or you can stiffen the gasket and it won't work (like the one you are probably replacing).
The expectation is that we have solved both the problem and the symptom.

Text of the user review is so basically i had at first intermittent gas burns, it would burn for a few minutes then shut off.  One guy claimed it was the ignitor so i swapped that out, it did the same, burn for a few seconds and turn off.  So the majority said to change these solenoids.  These things run from 6 bucks to about 11 bucks.  I chose these because they were amazons choice, but when i got them they looked like any other probably made in china part.  But unplug dryer,  you'll see the little gas valve shut off, turn that to your right, to shut off gas.  and that piece on the left that you see the plugs plugged in to.  there is two phillips head screws on the left bottom of each side (two screws) and that stainless steel looking bracket comes off.  Then you see the 2 solenoids,  they just pull off.  The one with the 3 prong,  it has a metal sleeve on the inside, just push it out and slide it on the bottom of the new solenoid.  The 2 prong one didn't  have that.  you will see though, there are one protrusion on top of each solenoid that the bracket has holes and fits that way only.  It's a no brainer, just put the solenoids on so it fits in the hole on the bracket, replug in those connectors,  put the bracket back on with the two phillips head screws, turn the gas back on,  plug back in and put some wet laundry in to test.  I'm testing now, but flame was large and hot.  So cheap fix,  it's working so can't complain for 11 bucks.  Oh my dryer must be over 25 years old,  old maytag dg4000 and its still working.. Text of the user review is This makes coffee. That isn't hard to do. However, for the price, it should be designed better.

It comes with a grey filter holder that replaces the K-cup adapter in the machine so you can use your own loose coffee. That's good. However, the design of the filter holder is such that it cannot stand up on its own. It would have been so much better to mold a ring at the bottom of the adapter so you could set it down while you remove the spent coffee grounds. So, why would you even want to remove the filter holder? Because of the way the lid is positioned, making it difficult to remove the filter (loaded with coffee) so it does not spill grains into the machine.

That leads us to the other problem... the clamp-down lid. Why it has two pieces amazes me. You first need to pull up on the chrome lid, and then pull up again to pull up the bottom portion. Why not simply use one lid? And then when it is up, it is still in the way of the filter or K-Cup.

I have been using tea bags to put coffee in so I can heat it in water on the stove. It works... every time, the coffee is smooth, and I can simply drop the spent bag of coffee into the compost bucket without any coffee grounds being spilled. The cost of the filters is minuscule. I spend a small fortune on a coffee maker and they prove that they can engineer something that doesn't work as well as something that costs next to nothing.

In a nutshell, it works as good as any other coffee maker like this, but don't expect a precision instrument. All this thing does is dribble water over a container of coffee grounds. That is it. Nothing special.. Main category of the item is Amazon Home. Item name is Cuisinart SS-10P1 Premium 72-Ounce Single-Serve Coffemaker, Stainless Steel & Cuisinart HomeBarista Reusable Filter Cup, Gray. Text of the user review is I have one of the first HE washer-dryer pairs produced by Kenmore, and they've service me well for many, many years. Last week the electric dryer stopped heating... everything else worked excluding the heat. I knew that the problem either had to be a thermal fuse or the heating element, and I strongly suspected the heating element. After doing a bit of research online, I was able to find the Whirlpool part number for the element, then looked to Amazon for parts availability...expecting that I wouldn't find anything due to the age of the dryer. I was delighted to find that this same element was used in a wide variety of dryers and was readily available from a number of outlets.

I chose this particular combination/package because it included the heating element and all of the thermal fuses in my dryer. For $24, I was certain to be able to replace whatever had failed within the unit... a VERY cheap price to pay to put a $1,500 dryer back in service. I did a bit more research online and found videos explaining how to replace the parts, making the repair somewhat simpler. In my case, I had to remove a total of 4 screws to obtain access to the heating element and 2 of the thermal fuses. The other 2 fuses would require me to truly disassemble the entire dryer, so I decided to take a chance on the easy route. With the continuity tester on my multimeter, I quickly learned that the problem was indeed a burned-out heating element. I replaced the element and the 2 associated thermal fuses, reassembled the parts, and was back in business in no time. For someone with a bit of mechanical knowledge and a 1/4 inch nut driver, the entire process would likely take 30 minutes or less. I am very pleased that the parts were near identical, quality replacements for the originals and that the dryer is working like new. I wouldn't hesitate to buy from this seller again if the need arose.. Main category of the item is Tools & Home Improvement.
